    <h3>Why Swedish Fish Remain the Most Iconic Swedish Gummy</h3>

    <p>Swedish Fish is where the story of Swedish candy in America begins. Developed by the Swedish confectioner Malaco in the late 1950s and originally exported to the US and Canadian markets, these fish-shaped gummies became one of the most recognizable candies in North America. The original recipe was designed to appeal to the North American palate — a single red berry flavor with a soft, chewy texture achieved through modified cornstarch rather than gelatin. That gelatin-free formulation, unusual for the era, was a deliberate choice rooted in Swedish candy-making philosophy: starch-based gelling was already standard in Scandinavian confectionery.</p>

    <p>Today, Swedish Fish are manufactured in North America by Mondelez International, so they are no longer a true import. But they remain the cultural touchstone — the candy that introduced millions of Americans to the concept of Swedish gummies. For anyone exploring the <a href="/candy/">candy and gummy category</a> for the first time, Swedish Fish are the starting point. The flavor is singular and unmistakable: a sweet, slightly berry-forward taste that resists easy description. It is not strawberry, not raspberry, not cherry — it is "Swedish Fish flavor," a category unto itself.</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <div class="tip-box-ico">i</div>
      <p><strong>Did you know?</strong> The original Swedish Fish red color was designed to represent the Swedish lingonberry. In Sweden, the candy was originally sold as "pastellfiskar" (pastel fish). The iconic fish shape was chosen because fishing is central to Swedish culture and exports.</p>
    </div>

