    <p>Bubs is a name that every Swedish candy enthusiast knows. Founded in Jönköping, Sweden, Bubs Godis has been producing gummies since the early 2000s and has earned a reputation for some of the finest candy in Scandinavia. Their skull gummies — known as "Bubs Cool Skalle" in Swedish — are the product that put them on the international map. The potato starch base creates a texture that is distinctly firmer and more elastic than anything you will find in American candy aisles. Each piece has a satisfying initial resistance when you bite, followed by a prolonged chew that releases layered fruit flavor. This is the Swedish gummy that converts skeptics into believers. The price is premium, but the quality gap between Bubs and mass-market American gummies is immediately obvious.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>The skull shape phenomenon.</strong> Skull-shaped gummies are a Swedish candy institution. In Sweden, they are known as "dödskallar" (death skulls) or "skallar" (skulls), and they have been a lördagsgodis staple since the 1990s. The shape was originally designed to appeal to children who found standard gummy bears too juvenile. Today, they are the most viral Swedish candy shape on social media — their distinctive look makes them instantly recognizable in unboxing videos and candy haul content.
