    <!-- SWEDISH VS AMERICAN GUMMIES -->
    <h2>Swedish vs. American Gummies — Key Differences</h2>

    <p>The differences between Swedish and American gummies go far beyond branding and packaging. Swedish candy is produced under stricter EU regulations and reflects a fundamentally different philosophy about confectionery. Here is a direct comparison across the categories that matter most.</p>

    <div class="vs-strip">
      <div class="vs-col">
        <h4>Swedish Gummies</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Gelling:</strong> Potato starch, pectin, modified starch — gelatin is less common</li>
          <li><strong>Sweetener:</strong> Cane sugar, glucose syrup — no high-fructose corn syrup</li>
          <li><strong>Colors:</strong> Natural colorants from fruit and vegetable extracts are standard</li>
          <li><strong>Flavors:</strong> Lingonberry, elderflower, salmiak, passion fruit — unique Nordic profiles</li>
          <li><strong>Texture:</strong> Firmer, chewier, more elastic — longer chew duration</li>
          <li><strong>Regulation:</strong> EU food safety standards — stricter additive restrictions</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="vs-col">
        <h4>American Gummies</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Gelling:</strong> Gelatin (pork or beef collagen) is the dominant gelling agent</li>
          <li><strong>Sweetener:</strong> High-fructose corn syrup or corn syrup is standard</li>
          <li><strong>Colors:</strong> Synthetic dyes (Red 40, Blue 1, Yellow 5) are widespread</li>
          <li><strong>Flavors:</strong> Strawberry, grape, cherry, watermelon — familiar fruit flavors</li>
          <li><strong>Texture:</strong> Softer, more rubbery, less firm — quicker chew</li>
          <li><strong>Regulation:</strong> FDA standards — more additives permitted</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>The ingredient quality gap is the primary reason Swedish gummies command higher prices in the US market. Potato starch costs more than gelatin. Natural fruit colorants cost more than synthetic Red 40. Imported cane sugar costs more than domestically produced HFCS. The price difference reflects a genuine quality difference — not just branding or import logistics.</p>

    <!-- SCANDINAVIAN CANDY TREND -->
    <h2>The Scandinavian Candy Trend in America</h2>

    <p>The surge in American demand for Swedish candy is not a fleeting social media trend — it is a structural shift in consumer preferences driven by three converging forces.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">2B+</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">views on the <strong>#SwedishCandy</strong> hashtag on TikTok as of early 2026 — making Scandinavian candy one of the most viral food categories on the platform. Unboxing videos, taste tests, and lördagsgodis hauls drive continuous discovery.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="star" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>TikTok & Social Media</h4>
        <p>Scandinavian candy unboxing videos began trending in 2023 and have not slowed down. The visual appeal of colorful pick-and-mix bags, unique shapes like skulls and Vikings, and the surprise factor of unfamiliar flavors make Swedish candy inherently shareable content. Creators like @candyfunhouse and @scandinaviancandy have built audiences in the millions.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="leaf" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Clean-Label Demand</h4>
        <p>American consumers are increasingly scrutinizing ingredient lists. The absence of HFCS, synthetic dyes, and gelatin in many Swedish gummies aligns perfectly with the clean-label movement. Parents in particular are seeking candy that avoids Red 40 and Yellow 5, which have been linked to hyperactivity concerns in some studies.</p>
