    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="faq-sec">
      <h2>Swedish Gummies — Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What makes Swedish gummies different from American gummies?</summary><p>Swedish gummies are typically made without high-fructose corn syrup, artificial colors, or synthetic dyes. Many use potato starch or pectin instead of gelatin, and natural colorants from fruit and vegetable extracts. The textures are firmer and chewier than most American gummies.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What is lördagsgodis?</summary><p>Lördagsgodis means "Saturday candy" in Swedish. It is a cultural tradition dating to the 1950s where Swedes eat candy only on Saturdays. This concentrated consumption pattern shaped Swedish candy into a premium, diverse category with hundreds of varieties.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Are Swedish gummies vegan?</summary><p>Many are — Swedish candy commonly uses potato starch and pectin instead of gelatin. Brands like Candy People, Kolsvart, and Bubs offer clearly labeled vegan options. However, not all Swedish gummies are vegan, so always check the ingredient list.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Why are Swedish gummies so popular on TikTok?</summary><p>Swedish candy went viral through unboxing videos, taste tests, and the visual appeal of colorful pick-and-mix displays. The #SwedishCandy hashtag has over 2 billion views. Unique shapes, cleaner ingredients, and unfamiliar flavors make them inherently shareable.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Where can I buy authentic Swedish gummies in the US?</summary><p>Amazon has the largest selection (Candy People, Bubs, Kolsvart, Malaco). Sockerbit stores in NYC and LA carry extensive selections. IKEA sells a small range. Online Scandinavian importers ship nationwide.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Do Swedish gummies contain gelatin?</summary><p>Many Swedish gummies are gelatin-free, using potato starch, modified starch, or pectin instead. However, some traditional brands still use gelatin. Look for products labeled "vegan" or "vegetarian" for guaranteed gelatin-free options.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What is the most popular Swedish candy?</summary><p>In Sweden: Malaco Gott & Blandat is the #1 bestselling candy mix. In the US: Swedish Fish is the most recognized Swedish-origin candy. Among authentic imports, Candy People and Kolsvart lead the American market.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Are Swedish gummies healthier than regular American gummies?</summary><p>Swedish gummies generally have cleaner ingredient lists — no HFCS, fewer artificial dyes, and more natural colorants. However, sugar content per serving is comparable (10-16g). The health advantage is primarily ingredient quality, not calorie reduction.</p></details>
    </section>

